The Maven directory structure:
src/main/java: Your Java source code goes here (strangely enough!)
src/main/resources: Other resources your application needs
src/main/filters: Resource filters, in the form of properties files, which may be used to define variables only known at runtime
src/main/config: Configuration files
src/main/webapp: The Web application directory for a WAR project
src/test/java: Unit tests
src/test/resources: Resources to be used for unit tests, but will not be deployed
src/test/filters: Resources filters to be used for unit tests, but will not be deployed
src/site: Files used to generate the Maven project Website




Maven lifecycle phases:

generate-sources: Generates any extra source code needed for the application, which is generally accomplished using the appropriate plug-ins
clean: Deletes the target directory and removes previous build files.
compile: Compiles the project source code
test-compile: Compiles the project unit tests
test: Runs the unit tests (typically using JUnit) in the src/test directory
package: Packages the compiled code in its distributable format (JAR, WAR, etc.)
integration-test: Processes and deploys the package if necessary into an environment where integration tests can be run
install: Installs the package into the local repository for use as a dependency in other projects on your local machine
deploy: Done in an integration or release environment, copies the final package to the remote repository for sharing with other developers and projects





validate: Checks whether the project structure and pom.xml are valid.
initialize: Initializes the build environment and sets up project properties.
generate-sources: Generates additional source code required for compilation.
process-sources: Processes and prepares the source code before compilation.
generate-resources: Generates resource files required by the application.
process-resources: Copies and filters resource files into the target directory.
compile: Compiles the project's main source code into .class files.
process-classes: Performs post-processing on compiled class files.
generate-test-sources: Generates source code required for testing.
process-test-sources: Processes test source files before compilation.
generate-test-resources: Generates resources needed for test execution.
process-test-resources: Copies and prepares test resources.
test-compile: Compiles the test source code.
process-test-classes: Performs post-processing on compiled test classes.
test: Runs unit tests using a testing framework such as JUnit.
prepare-package: Performs tasks required before packaging the application.
package: Packages the compiled code into a distributable format such as JAR or WAR.
pre-integration-test: Prepares the environment for integration testing.
integration-test: Executes integration tests against the packaged application.
post-integration-test: Cleans up the environment after integration testing.
verify: Verifies that the project meets quality and validation requirements.
install: Installs the packaged artifact into the local Maven repository.
deploy: Uploads the final artifact to a remote Maven repository for sharing.





Key Terms: Maven Projects

groupId :This element indicates the unique identifier of the organization or group that created the project. The groupId is one of the key identifiers of a project and is typically based on the fully qualified domain name of your organization.
artifactId :is the name of the jar without version. If you created it, then you can choose whatever name you want with lowercase letters and no strange symbols.
POM: A Project Object Model or POM is the fundamental unit of work in Maven. It is an XML file that contains information about the project and configuration details used by Maven to build the project. It contains default values for most projects.







