Core Framework & Stereotype Annotations:

Stereotype annotations inform Spring that a class is a managed component (Bean) and define its role within the application architecture.

@Component: Marks a class as a generic Spring-managed component for classpath scanning.
@Service: Specializes @Component to indicate that a class contains core business logic.
@Repository: Specializes @Component for data access objects (DAOs) and auto-translates database exceptions.
@Controller: Marks a class as a traditional web controller that handles HTTP requests and returns views.
@Configuration: Indicates a class contains source bean definitions using one or more @Bean methods.
@Bean: Placed on factory methods inside @Configuration classes to register the returned object as a Spring bean.
@ComponentScan: Configures the base packages where Spring looks for stereotype-annotated classes. 




Dependency Injection & Configuration

These annotations control how Spring wires dependencies together and sets configurations.

@Autowired: Instructs Spring to automatically inject a matching bean dependency into a field, constructor, or setter.
@Qualifier: Used with @Autowired to specify exactly which bean to inject when multiple beans of the same type exist.
@Primary: Gives higher preference to a specific bean when multiple candidates are available for injection.
@Lazy: Delays bean initialization until it is explicitly requested for the first time.
@Scope: Defines the lifecycle boundary of a bean, such as singleton or prototype.
@Value: Injects externalized values from application properties files, system environment variables, or SpEL expressions.
@Profile: Restricts the registration of a bean or configuration class to specific active application profiles.
@Import: Imports specific additional configuration classes into the current context.




Spring Web & REST Annotations:

These annotations handle incoming HTTP requests, route endpoints, and format web responses.

@RestController: Combines @Controller and @ResponseBody to mark a specialized controller that returns JSON or XML data.
@RequestMapping: Maps web requests to specific controller paths and can be applied at class or method levels.
@GetMapping: Shorthand for @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.GET) to retrieve data.
@PostMapping: Shorthand for @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.POST) to save data.
@PutMapping: Shorthand for @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.PUT) to update data.
@DeleteMapping: Shorthand for @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.DELETE) to remove data.
@PathVariable: Extracts a dynamic variable directly out of the URI path segment.
@RequestParam: Extracts query parameters or form parameters from the incoming request URL.
@RequestBody: Binds the incoming HTTP request body (like JSON) directly into a Java object.
@ResponseBody: Instructs Spring to serialize the method return value directly into the HTTP response body.
@ControllerAdvice: Intercepts exceptions globally across all controllers for centralized error handling.
@ExceptionHandler: Defines a specific method to handle exceptions thrown during web request processing.





Spring Boot Auto-Configuration:

These annotations handle the automatic setup features unique to Spring Boot.

@SpringBootApplication: Combines @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, and @ComponentScan to bootstrap the application.
@EnableAutoConfiguration: Instructs Spring Boot to automatically guess and configure beans based on classpath JAR dependencies.
@ConfigurationProperties: Binds entire groups of external hierarchy properties into a single type-safe POJO.
@ConditionalOnClass: Registers a bean only if a specified class file is present on the application classpath.
@ConditionalOnMissingBean: Registers a bean only if no other bean of the same type is already configured.




Data Access & Transaction Management:

These annotations manage transactions and control interactions with databases.

@Transactional: Configures transactional boundaries around a specific method or class to automate commit and rollback operations.
@Query: Defines custom JPQL or native SQL queries directly within a Spring Data Repository interface.
@Modifying: Enhances a @Query annotation to indicate that the executed query changes data (like updates or deletes). 








